did.abstract: The papers contain correspondence, memoranda, writings, photographs, and memorabilia, which document the career of John Farquhar Fulton as a neurophysiologist, medical historian, and bibliophile. The files also include personal and professional letters which reflect his involvement in organizations and projects including his work with the National Research Council, particularly in aviation medicine and in editing a medical history of World War II. Fulton's writings concern physiological and medical discoveries and those who made them. His close association with Harvey Cushing resulted in voluminous files on major writing and editing projects. Correspondence with family and colleagues reflects his travels, hospitality, and his collecting interests. Fulton's teaching and research are only sparsely represented in the papers.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The John Farquhar Fulton Papers document John Fulton's career as a neurophysiologist, medical historian, bibliophile, and administrator. They include correspondence, writings, organizational files, personal papers, and photographs which reflect Fulton's interest in the history of early scientific and medical discoveries. The papers also highlight Fulton's passion for book collecting and his efforts to foster notable collections in the history of medicine, including the Army Medical Library. This work culminated in the founding of the Yale Medical Historical Library, and the papers trace Fulton's close association with his collaborators on this project, Harvey Cushing and Arnold Klebs. The papers also contain an extensive record of Fulton's involvement, during World War II, with the work of the National Research Council, particularly with the Committee on Aviation Medicine and Subcommittee on Decompression Sickness, and his chairmanship of a project to prepare a medical history of the war.

The papers illustrate the possible reasons for Fulton's success in various undertakings: the extensive circle of his acquaintances; his consultative approach; his ability to engage large numbers of people, spread over two continents, in projects; and his overall enthusiasm. Fulton's expertise in the arts of the book (typography, layout, book design) and his careful attention to meticulous bibliographic records are also easily discernible. The papers have only sparse information (scattered correspondence, syllabi, and fragmentary notes) on Fulton's teaching and research. The files contain neither laboratory notebooks nor other research data from his work in the Yale Laboratory of Physiology.

The papers are arranged in five series which, for the most part, reflect Fulton's own arrangement of his files. The bulk of the papers dates from the 1920s to the 1960s. Series I, the General Files, consists of individual and organizational correspondence, which comprise almost two-thirds of the papers. Series II, Special Subjects, documents organizations in which Fulton was active as well as historical and bibliographic projects on which he worked. This series also includes correspondence, in addition to memoranda, agendas, minutes of meetings, and notes. Series III, Writings, contains documentation on Fulton's long and productive career as a writer and lecturer. It includes drafts of published and unpublished works arranged with correspondence related to these efforts. Series IV, Personal and Family Papers, includes John Fulton's memorabilia and personal and financial papers, as well as the correspondence of Lucia Fulton and other members of the Fulton, Wheatland, and Wheaton families. Series V, Visual Images, contains portraits; photographs of family and colleagues, travels, and residences; and several reels of undated 16 mm. film depicting social events and the results of physiological experiments.

The arrangement and the content of each series are more fully analyzed in the series description at the beginning of the inventory of that series. Because documentation on some topics appears in more than one series, cross-references are included in the inventory to each series. These are extensive but not all-inclusive. In the series inventories, Fulton's writings are referred to by the number assigned in the last published bibliography of his writings which appeared in the Journal of the History of Medicine and Allied Sciences, volume xvii, number 1, 1962.

Though the Fulton Papers were transferred to Manuscripts and Archives from the Yale Medical Historical Library in 1980, additional Fulton documentation, particularly that relating to the history of the Medical Historical Library, remains there. The bound volumes of Fulton's voluminous diary, collected correspondence, and additional writings and personal memorabilia are there, as are chapter drafts for Elizabeth Thomson's incomplete biography of Fulton. Fulton's diary is also available on microfilm. Where appropriate, this material has been cross-referenced with the indication "See:" or "See also: Cushing/Whitney Medical Historical Library."

bioghist.head: Biographical / Historical
bioghist.p: John Farquhar Fulton was born in St. Paul, Minnesota on November 1, 1899, son of John Farquhar Fulton, an ophthamologist, and Edith Stanley Wheaton Fulton. Fulton received his B.S. degree from Harvard University in 1921 and went as a Rhodes Scholar to Oxford University, receiving his B.A. degree from Magdalen College in 1923. He remained at Oxford as a Christopher Welch scholar during 1923-1925 and was granted M.A. and D. Phil. degrees in 1925. He was a demonstrator in physiology and worked closely with Sir Charles Sherrington during those two years. He then returned to Harvard to study for his medical degree.

After graduating in 1927, Fulton became an associate in neurological surgery at Peter Bent Brigham Hospital in Boston. He returned to Oxford from 1928 to 1930 as demonstrator in physiology and fellow of Magdalen College. He was appointed professor of physiology at Yale University in 1929 and, on his return to the United States the following year, was made Sterling professor of physiology. He also served as chairman of the Laboratory of Physiology. He relinquished these posts in 1952 to become the first Sterling professor of the history of medicine at Yale University. In 1960 he was named to head the new Department of History of Science and Medicine but did not live to assume the chair.

Fulton was considered an authority in comparative physiology of the primate brain, neurophysiology, aviation medicine, and medical history. He established the first primate physiology laboratory in the United States. He investigated the functional interrelations of various parts of the brain, the significance of overlapping somatic and autonomic motor functions and the effects of experimental lesions. With Carlyle Jacobsen, one of his students, he observed the effect of prefrontal lobotomy on a neurotic chimpanzee. This operation was later used on humans to alleviate certain mental disorders resistant to other types of treatment, but the most significant results of this work were the data revealed on the relationship between the brain and the intellect. Fulton was especially successful in relating neurophysiological backgrounds to modern clinical neurosurgery. He brought outstanding lecturers from around the world to enrich the educational experience of his students.

During the Second World War, Fulton served on the National Research Council as a member of the Committee on Aviation Medicine. He chaired the Sub-committee on Historical Records from 1940 to 1946, was vice-chairman of the Division of Medical Sciences in 1943, and chairman of the Sub-committee on Decompression Sickness from 1940 to 1946. He was also liaison to The British Medical Council. Fulton organized the Yale Aeromedical Research Unit to do research on physiological problems associated with aviation medicine. In addition, he created the Yale Faculty Committee for Receiving Oxford and Cambridge Children, Inc. to provide refuge for children in the United States during the bombing of Britain.

Almost from boyhood, Fulton was interested in collecting ancient books dealing with the development of science and medicine. He developed friendships with book dealers and other bibliophiles. His collection included approximately 11,000 titles dating from the sixteenth century to the twentieth century. Fulton brought together the collections of Harvey Cushing, Arnold Klebs, and his own to develop the Yale Medical Historical Library into one of the world centers devoted to the history of medicine and the sciences.

Fulton was considered an outstanding bibliophile. His interest in the history of early physiological and medical discoveries and in those who made them resulted in special collections and published bibliographies dealing with the works of Robert Boyle, Kenelm Digby, Michael Servetus and Girolamo Fracastoro.

Fulton wrote more than four hundred articles and nearly thirty books, including Physiology of the Nervous System , which was translated into Spanish, Russian, Portuguese, French, Japanese, and German, and the much praised Harvey Cushing, a Biography . He belonged to almost sixty societies, was honored by the governments of a dozen countries, and received nine honorary degrees, in addition to many awards and decorations.

Fulton was married in Oxford, England to Lucia Pickering, daughter of Richard Wheatland of Topsfield, Massachusetts on September 29, 1923. Soon after the couple returned from England, they established their residence at 100 Deepwood Drive in Hamden, Connecticut, where they entertained students, fellows, and visitors from around the world. John Fulton died on May 29, 1960.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: The John Farquhar Fulton papers are arranged in five series: I. General Files, 1910-1960. II. Special Subjects, 1892-1965. III. Writings, 1914-1960. IV. Personal and Family Papers, 1884-1988. V. Visual Images, 1899-1965.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This series reflects John Fulton's multi-faceted career and the wide travels, well-known hospitality, and energetic collecting typical of his professional and social milieu. Correspondence comprises the bulk of the files. Fulton's major correspondents include physiologists, physicians, bibliophiles interested in the history of medicine, book dealers, former students, learned institutions, editors and publishers, and family members. The files for institutions and associations indicate Fulton's broad range of professional involvement. They include the American Philosophical Society, History of Science Society, Rhodes Scholarship Trust, the American Medical Association, the Harvey Cushing Society, and the Institute for Advanced Study. In addition to correspondence, these files contain minutes, reports, agendas, notes, and other documents.

The series is arranged alphabetically by personal, corporate or institutional name, or periodical title. The container listing for the series includes a large number of cross-references directing the researcher from a personal or corporate name to related material. When correspondence with colleagues refers to their committee work together, additional material will be found under the name of the committee.

The series documents Fulton's preoccupation with history of medicine in the files of Leona Baumgartner, Logan Clendening, Dennis Duveen, Herbert Evans, William C. Gibson, Kenneth Franklin, Geoffrey Keynes, Sanford Larkey, Chauncey Leake, Arnold Muirhead, Charles Donald O'Malley, and Esther Rosencrantz. Fulton's devotion to libraries is demonstrated in the files for the Osler Library, the Gest Library, the Yale University Library, and the Yale Medical Library, and in his exchanges with librarians William W. Francis, Lloyd Stevenson, Henry Viets, and Dorothy Schullian and the Medical Library Association.

Day-by-day developments in the construction of the Yale Medical Library and the creation of the Yale Medical Historical Library are chronicled in the Arnold Klebs correspondence. It shows the frequency and intensity of the medical as well as bibliophilic exchanges between the two close friends. These files contain the original letters that Klebs wrote to Fulton as well as of Fulton's original letters to Klebs. Fulton apparently combined his files with correspondence found in Klebs's papers, when Klebs sent his library to New Haven. There is little correspondence between Fulton and the other major donor to the Medical Historical Library, Harvey Cushing. Fulton's exchanges with his mentor Cushing are almost entirely in the Harvey Williams Cushing Papers (MS 160).

Medical Historical Library staff members Madeline Stanton and Elizabeth Thomson collaborated with Fulton on many of his writing, editing, and book collecting projects. They also facilitated Fulton's assiduous record-keeping of his own experiences and coped with the voluminous files of his correspondence. Their files in this series, however, are routine. Additional material can be found in the Madeline Stanton Papers (MS 1482) and the Elizabeth Thomson Papers (MS 1623). Drafts for Elizabeth Thomson's unfinished biography of Fulton are in the Medical Historical Library.

The series provides evidence of Fulton's dedication to science and medical research. Fulton's early scientific experiences are documented in the files for Edward L. Mark and the "Bermuda Biological Station." Files on colleagues from Fulton's time at Oxford include those for Hugh Cairns, Edward G. T. Liddell, Archibald Malloch, and Wilder Penfield; those at the Peter Bent Brigham Hospital include Percival Bailey, Franc Ingraham, Richard Meagher, and Michel Pijoan. In exchanges with Howard Florey, Margaret Kennard, Carlyle Jacobsen, and Robert B. Livingston, Fulton discusses penicillin and neurophysiology as well as personal matters. The correspondence with Robert Yerkes traces the sharing of Yale facilities by Fulton and Yerkes in their work with chimpanzees.

The Yale Laboratory of Physiology was an important training ground for graduate, post graduate, and mid-career scientists. Former fellows of the Laboratory of Physiology continued to consult Fulton and to share research developments as they pursued their careers. There is correspondence in the series between Fulton and former research fellows Ebbe and Hebbel Hoff, Paul Bucy, Harold Lamport, Robert Burr Livingston, Donal Sheehan, Theodore Ruch, Hsiang-Tung Chiang, Derek Denny-Brown, Charles D. Aring, Allen D. Keller, Richard U. Light, William G. Mahoney, Arthur Earl Walker, and James W. Watts. The files of the Yale School of Medicine include the annual reports of the Department of Physiology/Physiological Sciences and the Laboratory of Physiology. Though voluminous, the bulk of these files concerns routine administrative matters.

Fulton's contribution to the World War II war effort, focused particularly on aviation medicine, can be seen in his correspondence with Hugh Cairns, Hugh DeHaven, and John Lawrence. In addition, the files for Eugene DuBois, Morris Fishbein, Louis Flexner, Lewis Weed, Detlev Bronk, E. Newton Harvey, Charles S. Stephenson, Harold Whittingham, and Solly Zuckerman address both medical subjects and Fulton's work for the National Research Council.

Files in the series can also be used to trace Fulton's efforts to assist those in need and to support the Allied effort during World War II. He helped European professionals such as David Nachmanson, Edith Meyer and Bruno Kisch when they sought refuge in the United States. He worked with CARE, Inc., American Defense, Harvard Group (which sought universal military training), Medical and Surgical Supply Company, and Committee to Defend America by Aiding the Allies.

Fulton's contribution to science included his work as an author and editor. Series I files for the Journal of Neurosurgery and Louise Eisenhardt document the creation of this journal. Though Series II contains the vast majority of correspondence concerning the Journal of Neurophysiology , Series I includes correspondence with fellow editors Ralph Gerard, Lorente de Nó, and Dusser de Barenne. Fulton's publishers also became his friends, as letters from Charles C. Thomas, Henry Schuman, George Banta Company, and W.B. Saunders Company attest. The voluminous correspondence with Charles C. Thomas includes exchanges regarding particular Fulton titles being published and consultations with Fulton about the evaluation of other authors' work.

Researchers interested in Fulton's correspondence with his family can consult files for his wife, Lucia Pickering Wheatland Fulton, his mother, Edith Fulton, his sisters, Margaret Berg, Laura Booraem, Louise Relf, and Florence Hubbell, and his brother-in-law, Ralph Hubbell. Ralph Hubbell's letters during World War II contain descriptions of his work with the Red Cross in the Soviet Union. Fulton also wrote to his in-laws, Mary and Richard Wheatland, parents of Lucia, and to her brother and sister, David and Martha Wheatland (who married Franc Ingraham). The frequent family letters, both to the Fultons and to the Wheatlands, add details to the already full account recorded in Fulton diaries.

Letters from unidentified authors are found at the end of the series, as are the annual Christmas letters and the Mill Rock Clarion that Fulton wrote and sent to a large list of correspondents. Both provide useful synopses of events and accomplishments.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This series contains files for fourteen major organizations and projects in which Fulton was an active participant. These files reflect themes in Fulton's career: bibliophilia relating to science and medicine, service to country, research interests in physiology, and contributions to scholarship through editorial work. The files are arranged in alphabetical order.

Fulton's life-long interest in books is demonstrated in several projects. Files under the heading "Bibliophilia" include correspondence, catalog listings, price quotations, invoices, and receipts from more than 150 book dealers starting in the 1920s. These files comprise one-fourth of the series. Further evidence of Fulton's interest in medical bibliography can be found in the files "Army Medical Library." These date from Fulton's presidency of the Army Medical Library's Association of Honorary Consultants and his chairmanship of its executive committee, when Fulton campaigned for the building of a national medical library and the preparation of a catalog of medical incunabula. Other bibliographic pursuits resulted in publications. Fulton had a strong collection of the work of the English physicist Robert Boyle. The "Boyle, Robert" files include booksellers' correspondence, as well as drafts and working files for several published bibliographies. Fulton's work on a census of the publication of the theologian and physician Michael Servetus and the completion of Harvey Cushing's bio-bibliography of anatomist Andreas Vesalius are also documented (see "Servetus, Michael" and "Vesalius, Andreas").

Fulton and Cushing shared interests in bibliography and medicine and worked together, first at Harvard and then at Yale. The files under the heading "Cushing, Harvey" show Fulton's devotion to his mentor. These include the organizational materials for Cushing's seventieth birthday celebration, birthday volume, and bibliography. There are also files from Fulton's involvement in the arrangements for Cushing's funeral, the handling of his estate, and memorial tributes. Files from the early 1940s relate to Fulton's oversight of Cushing's travel memoir, LePuy Diary . The files associated with Fulton's full-length study Harvey Cushing, a Biography constitute the largest portion under this heading. They include copies of advertising notices to help collect information and the responses received. There is also a separate alphabetical sequence of correspondence with publishers vying for the opportunity to publish the biography. Laudatory post-publication correspondence is included in two bound volumes.

Two sets of files document Fulton's contributions to both government and civilian programs during World War II. The National Research Council (NRC) files focus on the Committee on Aviation Medicine and Fulton's chairmanship of the Subcommittee on Decompression Sickness and of the Subcommittee on Historical Records. The NRC files contain minutes, agendas, reports, conference notes, and letters to and from members of the committees as well as with friends and NRC administrators. The Subcommittee on Historical Records files detail Fulton's commitment to publishing a multi-volume medical history of World War II, and the files contain volume outlines, assignments, and correspondence with authors. Correspondence with government officials traces the project through to its eventual demise. The files "Yale Faculty Committee for Receiving Oxford and Cambridge University Children, Inc." document arrangements by which Yale faculty brought British children to New Haven to care for them during the bombing attacks on Great Britain. The files contain correspondence with British parents, host faculty members, and committees at other universities.

Fulton's scientific research and teaching at Yale took place in the Laboratory of Physiology. The Laboratory of Physiology files document administrative aspects of some research projects, including lobotomy experiments and government-sponsored investigations in the field of aero-space medicine. There are no research notebooks, and teaching materials are limited to course outlines. A listing of fellows who worked in the Laboratory is included (folder 885). Fulton's expedition to collect and subsequent efforts to import and breed lemurs and Tarsius monkeys as experimental subjects are described in the section "Tarsius monkeys."

Files under several headings concern Fulton's editorial work. Correspondence under "Association for Research in Nervous and Mental Diseases" reveals his leadership during his two terms as the president in planning two annual meetings and publishing the resulting volumes: Volume 27, Frontal Lobes , in 1939 and Volume 20, Hypothalmus , in 1947. In recognition of his skills as an editor, Fulton was invited to revise two classic medical texts: Garrison's Textbook of Physiology and Howell's Introduction to Medical History . The folders under each title contain drafts, background materials, notes, correspondence with the publishers, and, in the case of the Howell book, exchanges with contributors. Fulton was founder and editor of the serial, Journal of Physiology . These files include correspondence concerning manuscripts submitted for publication and "top sheets" containing reviews of the manuscripts.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This series highlights Fulton's work as an author, reviewer, and editor of medical, biographical, and bibliographical materials. It provides thorough documentation of a large proportion of Fulton's writings, both published and unpublished. These include books, articles, introductions to works by others, obituaries, speeches, book reviews, and editorials. For any given title the files may contain drafts, notes, outlines, and correspondence associated with the writings. The files do not generally include the printed copies of Fulton's work. Many of these are available in the bound reprint volumes in boxes 256-261. For a few titles, additional material may be found in Series II. The listing for this series includes cross-references for these titles.

The writings are organized as either "Writings [listed in the bibliography]" or "Writings [not listed in the bibliography]." Boxes 262-283 contain the "Writings [listed in the bibliography]." These include any material for items listed in "Bibliography of John Farquhar Fulton," published in the Journal of the History of Medicine and Allied Sciences , volume XVII, number 1, 1962 (box 256, folder 1). Under this heading, folders are arranged in the same order as in this bibliography. The numbering sequence of the bibliography is in chronological order. Each bibliographic item has a unique number; the numbers are useful in distinguishing bibliographic items of similar title and date. Each folder description includes the unique bibliographic number, an abbreviated title, and the publication date in. parentheses. The numbering scheme for bibliographic items in the bound reprint volumes, however, does not match the one in the bibliography.

The files of "Writings [not listed in the bibliography]," boxes 284-293, are arranged in chronological order. Most of these files contain material relating to unpublished works. These include papers written while Fulton was a student and his dissertation.

The series reflects Fulton's research in medicine and physiology through his publications on topics such as the Babinsky reflex, frontal lobes of the brain, aviation medicine, penicillin, and primates. Documents associated with his authorship of the basic text Physiology of the Nervous System , which Fulton updated through several editions and which was translated into several languages, are also included, though all files associated with the revisions of Howell's Text of Physiology are found in Series II. At the time of his death; Fulton was in the process of revising Selected Readings in Physiology . The work was eventually published in 1966, under the guidance of Elizabeth Thomson. The files for this project are found in the Elizabeth Thomson Papers.

In addition the series highlights Fulton's interest in historical figures in science such as Robert Boyle, Kenelm Digby, Andreas Vesalius, Michael Servetus, and Girolamo Fracastoro. Fulton's writings on more contemporary figures, such as Benjamin Silliman, Harvey Cushing, Charles Sherrington, and William Osler, are also included. Files relating to Fulton's work to revise Garrison's Introduction to Medical History are in Series II.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: Series IV contains personal papers of John Farquhar Fulton and correspondence and memorabilia of other members of the Fulton, Langford, Wheatland, and Wheaton families. The series also includes genealogies and notes on family history. Correspondence of family members with John Fulton is filed alphabetically in Series I under the name of the correspondent. Files in the series are arranged alphabetically by the name of individual family members. Thereafter, materials are grouped according to record type.

John F. Fulton's files include clippings and financial records, such as check counterfoils and estate papers. There are also a few drafts for Fulton's diary, including some that are handwritten. These files also contain memorabilia from milestone events and from Fulton's travels. Other files concern funeral arrangements, obituaries, and memorials.

For John F. Fulton, Sr., there are case histories from his ophthalmological practice in nineteenth century St. Paul, Minnesota. These histories, in three bound volumes, include correspondence with patients and records of diagnoses and prescriptions.

There is a large quantity of Lucia Pickering Fulton's correspondence in the series. Long term correspondence with several family members and a few friends is arranged under the heading "Correspondence, alphabetical." Other correspondence is arranged in chronological order. This includes correspondence concerning John Fulton's publications and posthumous business affairs. Under the heading "Letters of condolence," there are expressions of sympathy and reminiscences about and tributes to John Fulton.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This series includes photo prints, negatives, sketches, and 16 mm motion picture film. These materials are arranged under four headings: "Chronological"; "Individuals"; "Buildings"; and "Film." Photographs from professional meetings and travel are filed under the heading "Chronological." Under "Individuals" there are portraits of Fulton, photographs of colleagues, friends and family, and research subjects. Photographs of Fulton's residences and offices are filed under "Buildings." Several undated reels of 16 mm. home movie film, probably made in England, perhaps in the 1920s, show social events. Additional reels include footage of experiments on research animals with impaired mobility.

accessrestrict.head: Conditions Governing Access
accessrestrict.p: Original audiovisual materials, as well as preservation and duplicating masters, may not be played. Researchers must consult use copies, or if none exist must pay for a use copy, which is retained by the repository. Researchers wishing to obtain an additional copy of non-commercially produced items for their personal use should consult the ordering reproductions information on the Manuscripts and Archives web site.
